WEBVTT

00:03.355 --> 00:06.298
OK, this is Ron Schorn about to interview Wes 
Traub. Wes, count down from 10 or something. 10, 9,

00:09.000 --> 00:11.363
8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1. OK, this is Thursday, April 22, 
1983. And this is Ron Schorn interviewing Wes

00:16.708 --> 00:25.836
Traub at the Center for Astrophysics here in 
Cambridge, Massachusetts. OK, Wes, your name is?

00:28.459 --> 00:29.800
Wesley Traub. And when were you born? 1940. Where? 
Wisconsin, Milwaukee. How did you first get

00:35.767 --> 00:37.470
interested in astronomy? Oh, well, I guess I was 
interested in astronomy like most kids. It's just

00:44.844 --> 00:45.725
interesting. But the thing that really 
interested me, I remember when I was a teenager,

00:46.286 --> 00:52.077
was spectroscopy, strangely enough. I mean, the 
idea of being able to measure the property of

00:54.698 --> 01:01.868
something that was far away by looking at the 
spectra, you know, Fraunhofer lines and all that

00:54.698 --> 01:01.868
sort of stuff. How did you learn about that? Book in 
the library, go to the Adler Planetarium or what?

01:06.755 --> 01:09.919
Well, we didn't have any planetariums, 
planetaria. It must have been from books, yeah.

01:13.585 --> 01:15.227
Where did you go to undergraduate school? I went to 
the University of Wisconsin at Milwaukee for...

01:19.951 --> 01:21.173
Undergraduate four years. Your major was? 
Physics. Actually, the physics, the major was

01:23.156 --> 01:25.619
complicated. It was called Applied Math and 
Engineering Physics. But it was basically lots of

01:28.884 --> 01:31.047
math and physics. And it was great because I didn't 
have to take any other courses. I didn't have to

01:34.732 --> 01:37.036
take any languages, hardly any English. I could 
take math courses all day. Where did you go to grad

01:41.222 --> 01:42.043
school? I went to the University of Wisconsin at 
Madison, the physics department. And I... was

01:50.107 --> 01:58.918
lucky enough then to meet up with

01:50.107 --> 01:58.918
Julian Mack, who was a a spectroscopist working on 
atomic spectroscopy, and was someone who was

02:00.248 --> 02:10.020
present in the late 20s and early 30s for the 
beginning of quantum mechanics. And near the end

02:10.300 --> 02:14.445
of his career, he was my professor at Wisconsin. So 
the stuff that I kind of liked, I just sort of lucked

02:14.485 --> 02:20.872
into at Madison. At that time, were you thinking of 
becoming an astronomer or were you going to be a

02:20.892 --> 02:24.737
physicist? Oh, no. What I was going to do then was to 
go into business with my father, who ran a lumber

02:25.726 --> 02:35.159
company, because I didn't know that people did 
this for a living. By the way, what year did you get

02:35.620 --> 02:40.227
your bachelor's and what year did you get your 
Ph.D.? Okay, bachelor's degree was in 1962, and

02:40.267 --> 02:47.817
Ph.D. was in 68, in physics. What was your 
dissertation on, by the way? Our thesis was on the

02:52.072 --> 02:57.645
abundance of lithium in sunspots.

02:58.226 --> 03:06.165
This was in the physics department, but the 
astronomy department was right upstairs, and so

02:58.226 --> 03:06.165
there was communication.

03:06.348 --> 03:12.079
a piece of equipment that had been invented at 
Wisconsin called a Pepsios interferometer. This

03:12.139 --> 03:24.863
was made up out of three Fabry-Perot 
interferometers put in series so that the light

03:12.139 --> 03:24.863
would come through each one of them, one after the 
other, and selectively isolate narrower and

03:12.139 --> 03:24.863
narrower bands of light Then you would scan the 
instrument from one wavelength to another by

03:25.163 --> 03:32.759
changing the air pressure in between the plates of 
the Fabry-Perot's. This is a wonderful

03:33.541 --> 03:42.480
instrument because it had all of the Ã©tendue, the 
light collecting power area and solid angle

03:33.541 --> 03:42.480
product of Fabry-Perot's. which meant that for 
astronomy, you could put a circular object at the

03:43.642 --> 03:58.497
entrance, not a slit, but a round aperture, like a 
star or a planet or the sun, part of the sun, and get

03:43.642 --> 03:58.497
all the light through the instrument at very high 
resolution. It had spectral resolutions of

03:58.597 --> 04:02.922
500,000 to a million in that range. When you 
finished your PhD, where did you get your first job

04:05.104 --> 04:08.367
and why? I got my first and last job here at the 
Smithsonian. And the connection was that while I

04:14.050 --> 04:25.647
was working on my thesis, there was Nat Carlton out 
here at the Smithsonian who had been working in the

04:14.050 --> 04:25.647
physics department at Harvard and also 
interested in Earth's upper atmospheric

04:26.167 --> 04:42.620
properties, became interested in planetary 
atmospheres early in his career by transitioning

04:26.167 --> 04:42.620
from the Earth's upper atmosphere to planetary 
atmospheres. And this was in the days before.

04:46.619 --> 04:47.180
well, 1968. It was in the days before much was known 
about abundances in planetary atmospheres. And

04:51.727 --> 05:02.505
in particular, the problem that he noticed was 
that the

04:51.727 --> 05:02.505
atmosphere of Mars was not well characterized. 
The pressures on Mars were postulated to be

05:04.962 --> 05:14.555
anywhere over a range of about 1,000 in surface 
pressure, and there just simply were no

05:04.962 --> 05:14.555
measurements that were highly reliable. And it 
was his thought, his idea, that this Pepsios

05:15.176 --> 05:31.898
interferometer could be used in the 
near-infrared, around 1 micron, to look at

05:15.176 --> 05:31.898
absorption lines of CO2 in the Martian 
atmosphere, and we could measure the abundance of

05:15.176 --> 05:31.898
CO2 that way. So while I was a graduate student, I 
came out here to the Smithsonian and helped set up

05:31.878 --> 05:42.409
and invent some of the materials for a pepsiose to 
be used in the near-infrared. And that experiment

05:43.330 --> 05:51.518
was set up at the Agassiz telescope, 61-inch 
telescope in Harvard, Mass. And the experiment

05:52.659 --> 05:57.764
was run simultaneously while I was a graduate 
student. We learned how to focus this thing in the

05:58.505 --> 06:01.648
infrared. and get it to measure the absorption 
lines on Mars. Who paid your bills at that time? Was

06:10.633 --> 06:11.474
it NASA? This was a NASA grant from, I think, yeah, 
from Planetary. I'd have to look back. Yeah, it was

06:20.602 --> 06:21.663
a bill. Bill Brunk was the person that we dealt with 
then, yeah, and for several years thereafter. Had

06:25.907 --> 06:30.471
Nat gotten this grant started before you came on 
board? It was about simultaneous. He got the money

06:33.863 --> 06:41.144
about the same time I came, and the grant was to pay 
for me to come here and to do this work, to buy the

06:33.863 --> 06:41.144
equipment. Yes? What about the, you mentioned the 
planetary atmospheres, not too much was known

06:43.343 --> 06:49.288
about them that you could really count on. Let's 
say the nose cone people, the reentry vehicle

06:49.368 --> 06:53.692
people could really take the hard stuff. Right, 
yeah. I mean, the issue here, excuse me, I should

06:54.053 --> 07:02.821
have said, the issue about Mars was a probe was to be 
sent there, and the question was, do you need a

06:54.053 --> 07:02.821
reentry vehicle? Could you use a parachute? How do 
you get something down to the surface of the

07:04.222 --> 07:06.384
planet? And so you wanted to know what the pressure 
was. That was the immediate practical problem. Go

07:09.887 --> 07:10.988
ahead, yeah. What about the state of the art of 
planetary astronomy in general when you came in?

07:16.289 --> 07:22.804
Was it pretty anti-Diluvian, pretty primitive 
compared to now? Well, there was a remarkable

07:23.947 --> 07:26.633
amount that was not known. I hadn't worked in 
planetary astronomy before this. physics

07:31.184 --> 07:34.067
laboratories doing atomic spectroscopy. And the 
sun was my major experience outside the

07:34.087 --> 07:39.073
laboratory. So I learned about planetary 
atmospheres. And so it didn't seem ancient to me or

07:42.857 --> 07:46.762
outmoded. It just seemed like what was. You always 
think that things are the way they are. You don't

07:50.867 --> 07:53.630
think, my god, why don't people know any better? 
These were hard experiments to do. And so to us, it

07:55.732 --> 08:00.938
was obvious then that nobody could have done a 
better experiment before. How many different

08:01.255 --> 08:06.003
major NASA contracts have you had? Not every year, 
but, you know, we worked on Pepsi Olsen, then we did

08:06.304 --> 08:12.956
this and stuff like that. Oh, a few, maybe

08:13.417 --> 08:20.850
four or five. The major ones that I remember are 
that we worked on this one grant, which extended

08:21.202 --> 08:31.355
for six, seven years, something like that, to work 
on planetary atmospheres. And we worked on many,

08:31.415 --> 08:40.908
many different aspects of planetary atmospheres 
and branched out and did things like interstellar

08:31.415 --> 08:40.908
lines and a lot of other stuff from that base. And 
actually, my planetary experience extends

08:42.089 --> 08:48.778
from... The first published paper was in 72, and 
the last one really was in 79. So that was the period

08:55.230 --> 08:59.882
in which we were using that grant to work. And after 
that, I became more interested in infrared and

09:00.464 --> 09:05.637
other things, and I started Working with other 
NASA grants for other purposes. Run out of

09:10.210 --> 09:10.931
planets? There's plenty of stars. Well, 
actually, I moved from doing that to doing far

09:12.934 --> 09:19.906
infrared spectroscopy with a Fourier transform 
spectrometer. And part of the reason, well, this

09:20.628 --> 09:26.618
is getting ahead of the story, but we went to Bill 
Brunk. I mean, that was the start of my independent

09:27.499 --> 09:31.506
research work. noticed that there was a lack of 
measurement in the far infrared, around 100

09:31.840 --> 09:42.049
micron wavelength, because that part of the 
atmosphere is totally absorbing due to water

09:31.840 --> 09:42.049
vapor, rotational absorptions. And there was, at 
the time, here at the Smithsonian, a dramatic

09:42.910 --> 09:50.717
experiment that Giovanni Fazio had been running 
for a few years. This was a one-meter diameter

09:51.137 --> 10:01.206
telescope that was carried to about 28 kilometers 
altitude by large balloons, helium-filled

09:51.137 --> 10:01.206
balloons from Palestine, Texas. And the thought 
here was, gee, why don't we build an instrument to

10:01.186 --> 10:09.338
look at spectral lines? Because all that was being 
done then was filters, broadband photometric

10:09.438 --> 10:18.491
measurements of planets, among other things, 
too. Outer planets we looked at with that

10:19.253 --> 10:20.915
instrument. But I was interested in looking at the 
spectra. And so we proposed to the Planetary

10:24.380 --> 10:29.067
Division, to Bill Brunk, in fact, to build an FTS to 
go onto this instrument. And one of the things, we

10:35.039 --> 10:46.233
had a number of things that were of interest, but 
one of the things was to look at the atmospheres of

10:35.039 --> 10:46.233
Venus and Mars and see there was a whole number of 
rotational lines in the far infrared that we

10:35.039 --> 10:46.233
should be able to see there. We did receive the 
money. I received the grant, $150,000 to build

10:48.936 --> 10:52.040
this instrument. And we built it and flew it. It 
turned out to be a very difficult thing to do to

10:56.755 --> 11:00.700
point this telescope accurately. And so, in fact, 
we never ever did use it to record any planetary

11:00.800 --> 11:05.926
spectra. But we went on to look at the Earth's 
atmosphere. And my career on atmospheres has

11:10.571 --> 11:16.679
evolved into the Earth's atmosphere then. And 
we've done a lot of work since then on the

11:16.699 --> 11:19.762
terrestrial atmosphere. But that's not planets. 
That's the Earth. Oh, may I continue on this? Yeah,

11:28.274 --> 11:38.294
it just occurred to me that as an interesting 
sidelight, my interest in planets has followed my

11:28.274 --> 11:38.294
other interests, which are spectroscopy, but 
really interferometry. I just am fascinated by

11:38.454 --> 11:41.761
the idea of interfering beams of light. And 
another experiment that I've worked on for the

11:42.442 --> 11:47.552
last decade is using high angular resolution 
separated telescopes to look at stars and

11:47.752 --> 11:58.888
materials around stars perhaps. And so an 
instrument that we have now built on Mount Hopkins

11:59.488 --> 12:11.245
uses telescopes that are separated by up to about 
38 meters to do a modern Michelson stellar

11:59.488 --> 12:11.245
interferometer type experiment. And one of the 
things that we've been looking at recently is, can

12:11.225 --> 12:24.200
this instrument detect planets around other 
stars by looking at the very small wobble that you

12:11.225 --> 12:24.200
would see in the position of the star as it moves 
across the sky? It's an incredibly difficult

12:24.881 --> 12:35.274
problem, but it comes back to searching for 
planets instead of looking at ones that you know,

12:24.881 --> 12:35.274
and that kind of amuses me. What wavelength is the 
uranoprometer after wavelengths? The one at

12:38.512 --> 12:40.595
Mount Hopkins. The Mount Hopkins instrument. 
This would be a visible and near-infrared

12:41.898 --> 12:47.947
instrument, visible and K-band instrument. How 
was your relationship with NASA when they were

12:49.290 --> 12:53.597
funding? Who's funding you now, by the way, NSF or? 
We have a little money through the University of

12:56.942 --> 13:03.152
Wyoming from the NSF for this project. 
interferometer project, which is called IOTA for

13:04.060 --> 13:09.607
Infrared Optical Telescope Array on Mount 
Hopkins. And there is some other funding for that

13:10.609 --> 13:19.661
project from NASA also, and internally from the 
Smithsonian. But the bulk of my funding is for

13:20.983 --> 13:29.334
looking at the Earth's atmosphere, because I run 
these two sorts of projects parallel, or run with

13:20.983 --> 13:29.334
them. And the bulk of the funding is from the upper 
atmospheric division at NASA to look at the

13:32.090 --> 13:36.116
Earth's atmosphere.

13:39.442 --> 13:43.408
How would you say NASA does when they're giving you 
money? Do they butt in? Are they getting worse? Are

13:45.271 --> 13:46.072
they getting better? Do they generally let you do 
what you said you were going to do, or what? Feel

13:52.141 --> 13:53.203
free. No, I have nothing but happiness to report on 
that. I mean, every experiment that I've been

13:57.047 --> 14:06.020
involved with in the planetary division and in the 
upper atmospheric division, we've proposed to do

13:57.047 --> 14:06.020
work. NASA has almost always given us essentially 
all of the money that we've asked for. I can't

14:12.650 --> 14:18.638
recall a single case where somebody has come and 
said, you ought to be doing this and not that. And on

14:19.219 --> 14:22.684
top of that, after you do the work, I haven't, 
nobody's ever come back and said, well, you

14:23.238 --> 14:36.495
promised to do X, Y, and Z, but you only did X and half 
of Y because, you know, you always end up sort of

14:23.238 --> 14:36.495
thinking you can do more than you actually do, and 
sometimes you do things that you never thought you

14:23.238 --> 14:36.495
would do. So it always amazes me that people never 
come along and inventory what you put in your first

14:36.535 --> 14:44.625
proposal and see whether or not that's what you 
actually reported three years later. It's

14:44.685 --> 14:47.329
astonishing. I hope they don't start doing it. 
There was a comment that I read somewhere that...

14:53.140 --> 15:00.761
By definition, of course, discoveries cannot be 
foreseen because someone had been accused by some

14:53.140 --> 15:00.761
government agency of not foreseeing this 
discovery. Yes, of course, that's ridiculous.

15:05.493 --> 15:10.240
You know, some people object to having to write 
proposals and say, oh, well, this is a lot of busy

15:05.493 --> 15:10.240
work. I think it's a good idea because it helps you 
clearly formulate your ideas. You think of things

15:14.987 --> 15:19.674
that you might not have thought about when you're 
forced to write it down and defend it in front of

15:14.987 --> 15:19.674
people. And so I don't have any problem with that. 
What do you consider the most important piece of

15:26.465 --> 15:33.475
work you've done in planetary astronomy?

15:37.083 --> 15:42.689
Oh, there are several things that really excited 
me when I looked at them. The first experiment I did

15:45.452 --> 15:51.298
was to discover oxygen on Mars. And this was a big 
thrill because I'd only discovered one other

15:51.519 --> 15:59.187
thing once before in a laboratory setting. And to 
go out and actually look through a telescope and

15:59.287 --> 16:04.913
discover a molecule that nobody had ever seen 
before was really a very exciting thing for me. And

16:08.772 --> 16:12.218
that was 1972 we published that. That was a 
follow-up of the work that had been done on CO2 on

16:13.140 --> 16:16.585
Mars. And so I always remember that fondly, 
perhaps because it was the first thing. I don't

16:22.035 --> 16:25.620
know if it was the most important, but it certainly 
was fun for me. Okay, that was my next question,

16:26.041 --> 16:28.786
what was the most fun, and you just answered it. Did 
you ever... run into any real bogs or morasses or

16:31.657 --> 16:40.791
blind alleys or things where you said, oh, we never 
should have tried this or something like that?

16:40.811 --> 16:54.593
Well, there was a whole body of work that we did on 
looking at Jupiter and Saturn in lines of methane,

16:40.811 --> 16:54.593
ammonia, methane and ammonia, and hydrogen lines 
also. And I guess I have a regret. I mean, it was a

16:57.899 --> 17:04.593
morass in the sense that we took a ton of data on 
spectral lines that were not well characterized.

17:04.654 --> 17:08.281
We didn't know what the temperature dependence of 
their oscillator strengths was. But we did it in

17:09.243 --> 17:14.134
the hope that these things would be learned later. 
Nat Carlton and I spent many, many, many nights at

17:14.300 --> 17:34.385
the 60-inch telescope on Mount Hopkins that he 
actually built, and I helped him with a little bit

17:14.300 --> 17:34.385
in those days, taking data on these outer planets 
that never really ended up being digested and

17:14.300 --> 17:34.385
published in the kind of form that I would have been 
happy with. There are a few reports out, but we saw a

17:34.806 --> 17:43.176
lot of things, like ammonia coming and going, and 
many, many things that never really quite got

17:43.713 --> 17:45.495
tidied up the way they should have been and 
published. How have NASA's dollars affected

17:47.757 --> 17:56.647
planetary astronomy

17:47.757 --> 17:56.647
in general? Well, I'm not sure how to answer that, 
because I actually... Where would we be without

17:56.667 --> 18:01.892
it? Oh, well, unquestionably, none of this stuff 
would ever have been done at this level if there

18:03.013 --> 18:11.442
wasn't funding from NASA to do it. I mean, I would 
have gone off to work for IBM or something like

18:12.063 --> 18:15.086
that. Well, in fact, that was my other promising 
offer. Instead of coming to a much lower-paying

18:20.431 --> 18:27.237
job here at the Smithsonian, doing something that 
sounded like a lot of fun. So if it were not for the

18:28.418 --> 18:34.945
NASA support, we would know none of this stuff, I 
think, now. Back when you started, were you aware

18:36.906 --> 18:39.589
of any... snobbishness on the part of quote real 
unquote astronomers towards people who worked on

18:40.548 --> 19:07.602
the planets oh well yes uh i mean i i'm even more 
aware of uh of this well we were talking about

18:40.548 --> 19:07.602
second class status for planetary astronomers 
you said you were even more aware of that well well

18:40.548 --> 19:07.602
the thing is i i was a physicist i am a physicist and i 
came from the physics department and I learned a

19:07.919 --> 19:14.946
little astronomy by going up and taking a few 
courses and reading books, but I wasn't a real

19:07.919 --> 19:14.946
astronomer. And there are real astronomers and 
there are outsiders. So I'm perfectly aware of the

19:17.989 --> 19:28.360
fact that real astronomers are different than 
people who get into the field by some other back

19:17.989 --> 19:28.360
door, like studying physics. And planetary 
astronomy is one of those outside of real

19:33.316 --> 19:35.920
astronomy areas also. But at the Smithsonian 
here, we're all coexisting quite happily, and

19:36.641 --> 19:44.392
I've never really had any problems with it. I enjoy 
what I'm doing, and other people, I think, respect

19:44.913 --> 19:48.338
what we're doing. Do you think over the last 30 
years or so that the planetary astronomers have

19:48.919 --> 19:58.172
managed to get up to about equal status with the 
stellar and galactic people? Well, it... No, I

20:02.071 --> 20:03.974
don't think that that's ever the case. I mean, if 
you study galaxies and what the distribution of

20:04.075 --> 20:20.383
galaxies is, like some of the people in this 
building do, you will always attract much more

20:04.075 --> 20:20.383
attention and be considered to be a real 
astronomer by the general public than if you study

20:04.075 --> 20:20.383
planets. I think there's certainly such a great 
interest in the part of the general public in

20:20.363 --> 20:36.006
planets because that's where people live and 
there might be life that this is, you know, one

20:20.363 --> 20:36.006
doesn't feel like, I don't feel like a second class 
citizen having done this sort of thing. Do you

20:36.026 --> 20:40.633
think planetary astronomers have done a good job 
publicizing themselves to the general public?

20:42.925 --> 20:49.553
I think that the best publicist in the world for 
astronomy was a planetary astronomer. Carl

20:49.613 --> 21:00.245
Sagan, in my opinion, did a wonderful job 
publicizing the adventure of astronomy and, of

20:49.613 --> 21:00.245
course, of planetary astronomy and science in 
general. I don't think he's appreciated by a lot of

21:01.306 --> 21:08.595
other astronomers or maybe even planetary 
astronomers.

21:09.622 --> 21:27.226
I think that Carl has done a wonderful job and that 
people really appreciate and enjoy his programs a

21:09.622 --> 21:27.226
lot and that he brought a lot of people very close to 
being interested in what goes on at telescopes and

21:09.622 --> 21:27.226
the interpretation of the results from 
telescopes. I think he's done a very good job for

21:27.607 --> 21:28.929
it.

21:32.153 --> 21:33.755
That's a very general question. Do you think that 
all the new results that have come out on solar

21:37.803 --> 21:45.834
system objects in the last 30 years have affected 
the public's ideas to any extent? Talking about

21:46.155 --> 21:51.642
the public that reads, for

21:46.155 --> 21:51.642
example. Well, I mean, yes. I mean, it helps by 
knowing more about, well, by knowing, for

21:53.344 --> 22:06.122
example, that there's not life on Mars, but that we 
have looked and that there was a possibility and,

21:53.344 --> 22:06.122
well, it didn't pan out. and just the general 
intellectual excitement of thinking about

22:06.355 --> 22:10.922
something that's nearby. I think people don't 
relate to stars. My personal opinion, the general

22:14.688 --> 22:18.855
public doesn't relate to things that are far away. 
They always want to know, well, how does this

22:19.255 --> 22:21.499
affect me? If you tell them what you do and that you 
study astronomy or planets, they say eventually

22:21.539 --> 22:33.898
their question is, aside from polite

22:21.539 --> 22:33.898
questions, A lot of people, the bulk of people in 
the United States say, well, really, how does this

22:34.115 --> 22:39.863
affect me and why should I be supporting it? That's 
what they think deep down inside. And if it's

22:42.146 --> 22:48.895
something that can relate to a person, like 
searching for life or looking at other planetary

22:42.146 --> 22:48.895
surfaces that are like the Earth. Or deflecting 
killer asteroids. Or deflecting killer

22:50.497 --> 22:51.919
asteroids. Or preventing the ozone hole from 
growing or the greenhouse. Well, yes. Now, that's

22:56.565 --> 22:59.008
something that comes incredibly close to home. 
Well, it used to be that people would talk about, or

22:58.988 --> 23:15.302
I would say things like, it's of interest to study 
other planets, like Venus and Mars, because they

22:58.988 --> 23:15.302
tell you something about the Earth, because 
they're very similar, and that we ought to make

22:58.988 --> 23:15.302
these comparative studies. And those are sort of 
vague, generalized arguments that I don't think

23:16.043 --> 23:21.348
the general public would buy. But if you discover 
all of a sudden that the ozone is disappearing over

