23:50.288 --> 23:51.309
Personal question here. Now, I can recall you and 
Matt and you and I and Andy and all these fights

23:51.349 --> 23:59.961
about your Pepsios data. What ever went on with all 
that? Well, the key thing that sticks in my mind

24:03.987 --> 24:11.858
about Pepsios is that we did a a mind-stretching 
experiment with it, which was to measure wind

24:12.783 --> 24:17.628
velocities on Venus. This was a suggestion that 
was brought to us by Mike Belton one time when Mike

24:18.349 --> 24:28.400
and Don Hunton came up to visit the Pepsios on Mount 
Hopkins. And they looked at this wonderful

24:28.941 --> 24:33.866
instrument and said, gee, you can measure wind 
velocities on Venus. And we said, oh, we can? We had

24:35.728 --> 24:39.432
been looking at carbon dioxide lines in the upper 
atmosphere of Venus cloud tops. And then we

24:42.356 --> 24:45.327
realized that, yes, of course they're bright. 
This is a wonderful experiment. And Nat and I

24:46.733 --> 24:50.046
worked on this for several years. We worked very 
hard to try and make sure that there were not any

24:50.768 --> 25:05.230
instrumental biases, because what we were 
looking for was a very tiny shift in the wavelength

24:50.768 --> 25:05.230
of a spectral line formed in the atmosphere of 
Venus from sunlight. The sunlight bounced off the

25:05.250 --> 25:07.974
top of the atmosphere of Venus. Some of it was 
absorbed in a CO2 line. And if the atmosphere was

25:10.478 --> 25:20.633
moving, if there were winds or velocities from 
mass motions in the atmosphere, you would see a

25:10.478 --> 25:20.633
small Doppler shift. The Doppler shift would 
translate into a wavelength shift that you could

25:20.653 --> 25:23.898
measure on Earth. So we measured Doppler shifts of 
these spectral lines at various places on the

25:24.899 --> 25:39.000
planet so that you could compare the light that you 
saw reflected from the limb with the light

25:24.899 --> 25:39.000
reflected from the terminator and see if there was 
a wavelength shift. And if there was a wavelength

25:39.166 --> 25:43.651
shift, you could attribute that to a rotational 
velocity of the upper atmosphere. And we observed

25:44.712 --> 26:00.750
this for several years when Venus was on different 
sides of the sun, in different configurations,

25:44.712 --> 26:00.750
under different circumstances, and measured 
what I am convinced is a very good measurement of

25:44.712 --> 26:00.750
100 meter per second winds in the upper atmosphere 
of Venus. And we published that paper. There

26:05.416 --> 26:06.557
was... Well, this is not my favorite story, but 
there was skepticism, mostly, from our good

26:07.617 --> 26:30.057
friend Andy Young, who took it upon himself to 
decide that there were a lot of instrumental

26:07.617 --> 26:30.057
effects in this complicated instrument that 
could have caused these winds to appear to be

26:07.617 --> 26:30.057
shifting when, in fact, they weren't. I thought 
that I had taken out all of these effects by

26:31.759 --> 26:36.223
calibration and repeated measurements uh... and 
uh... was convinced that he was wrong but we

26:36.490 --> 27:04.540
invited him up and he came up and worked on the 
mountain top with us for a week or so one time the

26:36.490 --> 27:04.540
results unfortunately were inconclusive we were 
not able to make experiments which showed that the

26:36.490 --> 27:04.540
instrument did have biases in it but we certainly 
were able to make the instrument produce biased

26:36.490 --> 27:04.540
results by pushing hard enough which i knew that 
you could do these were not the circumstances

26:36.490 --> 27:04.540
under which the wind velocities were measured The 
outcome of that was, I believe, that... And this

27:05.819 --> 27:26.708
I'm not sure about because I don't have it 
documented, but I do believe that Andy spoke

27:05.819 --> 27:26.708
against these results to a number of people and 
said they can't possibly be measuring wind

27:05.819 --> 27:26.708
velocities there. This is a figment of their 
imagination or whatever. The instrument is full

27:29.672 --> 27:31.134
of biases. And... essentially caused these 
results not to be widely quoted. I still, to this

27:42.929 --> 27:56.194
day, am absolutely convinced that we did take out 
the biases and that we could see these effects and

27:42.929 --> 27:56.194
that we did measure 100 meter per second winds and 
that there was absolutely nothing wrong with the

27:42.929 --> 27:56.194
measurements. But I think it's a very unfortunate 
thing. Well, for me at least, it's personally

27:59.172 --> 28:09.747
unfortunate that Andy felt so strongly about this 
that he went around and told people that these

27:59.172 --> 28:09.747
results were suspect. And in fact, I remember 
clearly from one committee meeting that was held

28:09.767 --> 28:25.168
to try and summarize the results of the Venus upper 
atmosphere, I had a call one day from somebody who

28:09.767 --> 28:25.168
was responsible for writing up these results. 
uh... results uh... jerry schubert and uh... he

28:25.705 --> 28:51.595
said you know that you know we're not gonna mention 
these results because uh... we think that they

28:25.705 --> 28:51.595
were contaminated or flawed or something like 
that and it was a result of uh... andy's lobbying i

