30:09.297 --> 30:19.886
research is very exciting because we have these 
two problems that are clearly in the public mind.

30:20.166 --> 30:28.474
One is of the buildup of carbon dioxide and the 
increasing temperature of the Earth, which has

30:20.166 --> 30:28.474
been advocated and promoted most strongly by a 
former planetary person, Jim Hansen, at Goddard,

30:29.028 --> 30:38.204
whatever it is in New York City. It's Goddard in New 
York. And I happen to think Jim is right. I remember

30:45.317 --> 30:53.652
Jim's original work in looking at the atmosphere 
of Venus and discovering from inverting

30:54.290 --> 31:06.904
calculations that the particles in the 
stratosphere of Venus had to be spherical globs

30:54.290 --> 31:06.904
with an index of refraction of one point 
something, something, something, which was an

30:54.290 --> 31:06.904
absolute. Or three. You know this problem, too. 
And just to diverge for a second, I remember this

31:09.987 --> 31:13.871
result so clearly. I thought, this is 
astonishing. How could he possibly say that

31:15.092 --> 31:18.256
nothing in nature is ideal like that? That's a 
physicist idealization. But he said that this is

31:20.648 --> 31:22.251
really the way it was. And I remember we had a 
graduate student. And I put the graduate student

31:25.255 --> 31:30.003
to this problem of saying, look, here's the 
handbook of chemistry and physics. Why don't you

31:30.083 --> 31:35.872
look up all the substances that have index of 
refraction in this range and see what that could

31:30.083 --> 31:35.872
possibly be? And the student came back and he said, 
well, there's sulfuric acid and there's other

31:36.613 --> 31:40.840
stuff. And we sort of chuckled and said, well, 
obviously, Very uninformed comment of ours.

31:45.974 --> 31:51.380
Obviously, these clouds could not be made out of 
sulfuric acid particles, and sort of dropped it at

31:45.974 --> 31:51.380
that point. And months and a year later, this was 
really taken up seriously. I guess that was Louise

31:57.667 --> 31:59.870
Young that came up with that. Louise Young 
commented on it. Jeffrey Sill, you were involved,

32:03.694 --> 32:06.997
I think. Yeah, yeah. And so a number of people came 
up with it, but it was... It was a major failure on my

32:12.522 --> 32:20.940
part not to follow that up vigorously after that 
because it was a very interesting result.

